nihills.lm <- lm(time ~ dist+climb, data=nihills)

(b) Using the F-test result, make a tentative choice of model

The ‘anova()’ function computes analysis of variance (or deviance) tables for one or more fitted model objects. When given a sequence of objects, ‘anova()’ tests the models against one another in the order specified.

In this context, based purely on the output of the ‘anova()’ function, one tends to choose the model number 2 as the one that better describes the data, since the p-value for the F-test is considered very low. However, it is not the final decision yet, since we still need to analyse the diagnostic plots.

Proceed to examine diagnostic plots. Are there any problematic observations?

In order to analyse the diagnostic plots, we can simply plot the fitted models. We may begin our analysis under the light of Model number 1:

par(mfrow = c(2,2))

# Model 1:
plot(nihills.lm)

The first graph, “Residuals versus Fitted”, shows if the residuals have non-linear patterns. It is possible to notice, from our plot, a “V” shaped curve, indicating that something is not well adjusted.

The second graph, “Normal Q-Q”, shows if residuals are normally distributed. It is possible to notice that most part of the residuals seem to follow the straight line well, but some of them, specially the “Seven sevens”, deviate.

The third graph, “Scale-Location”, shows if residuals are spread equally along the ranges of predictors. One can notice that in our graph most part of the residuals seem to be randomly spread, but the last three points seem to follow a straight line with a steep angle (Seven sevens, and Annalong Horseshoe).

Finally, the fourth graph, “Residuals versus Leverage”, helps us to find influential cases. One can notice the points related to Seven sevens and Annalong Horseshoe are highlighted in this context.

From the analysis of the Model number 1, it is possible to highlight the points Seven sevens and Annalong Horseshoe as problematic ones, in the sense that they are highly influential and may distort the entire analysis.

Now, considering Model number 2:

par(mfrow = c(2,2))

# Model 2:
plot(nihills2.lm)

It is possible to notice that the point “Seven Sevens” still is identified as an influential one, even considering a different model.

What happens if these points are removed? Refit both of the above models, and check the diagnostics again.

Apply the lm.ridge() function to the litters data, using the generalized cross-validation (GCV) criterion to choose the tuning parameter. (GCV is an approximation to cross-validation.)

(a) In particular, estimate the coefficients of the model relating brainwt to bodywt and lsize and compare with the results obtained using lm().

The function ‘lm.ridge()’ is used to fit a linear model by Ridge regression. That said, one can compute:

library(MASS)
##

## 
##     hills
# Ridge regression with lambda = 0:
litters.ridge_l0 <- lm.ridge( brainwt ~ bodywt + lsize, 
                           data = litters, lambda =0 )
litters.ridge_l0
##                  bodywt       lsize 
## 0.178246962 0.024306344 0.006690331

                           data = litters, lambda = seq(0,0.1,0.001)))
## modified HKB estimator is 0 
## modified L-W estimator is 0

As can be seen, using the generalized cross-validation (GCV) criterion it was possible to choose the tuning parameter, ‘0.1’. Now using \(\lambda=0.1\) we have the final Ridge regression:

(b) Using both ridge and ordinary regression, estimate the mean brain weight when litter size is 10 and body weight is 7. Use the bootstrap, with case-resampling, to compute approximate 95% percentile confidence intervals using each method. Compare with the interval obtained using predict.lm().

We can use the library ‘boot’ to asses the Bootstrap functions in R.

# In order to estimate the mean brain weight when litter size is 10 and body weight is 7:
library(boot)
## 
## Attaching package: 'boot'
## The following object is masked from 'package:lattice':
## 
##     melanoma
set.seed(2019)

# Estimating the Mean - ordinary linear regression:
mean_litters.lm <- unname(litters.lm$coefficients[1] +
                            7*litters.lm$coefficients[2] +
                           10*litters.lm$coefficients[3])

# Boot function - Ordinary linear regression:
mean_lm <- function(data, indices) {
  d <- data[indices,] # allows boot to select sample 
  fit <- lm(d$brainwt ~ d$bodywt + d$lsize, data = d)
  return(fit$coefficients[1]+7*fit$coefficients[2]+10*fit$coefficients[3])
}

#Bootstrapping with 10^4 replications:
results_lm <- boot(data = litters, statistic= mean_lm, 
                   R = 10^4, stype = "i")

# 95% confidence interval:
boot_ci_lm <- boot.ci(results_lm, conf = 0.95, type="all")
#boot_ci_lm

# Estimating the Mean - Ridge regression:
mean_litters.ridge <- coef(litters.ridge)[1] + 
                    7*coef(litters.ridge)[2] +
                   10*coef(litters.ridge)[3]

# Boot function - Ridge regression:
mean_ridge <- function(data, indices) {
  d <- data[indices,] # allows boot to select sample 
  fit <- lm.ridge(d$brainwt ~ d$bodywt + d$lsize, data=d, lambda = 0.1)
  return(coef(fit)[1]+7*coef(fit)[2]+10*coef(fit)[3])
}

#Bootstrapping with 10^4 replications - RIDGE:
results_ridge <- boot(data = litters, statistic = mean_ridge, 
                      R = 10^4, stype = "i")

# 95% confidence interval - RIDGE:
boot_ci_ridge <- boot.ci(results_ridge, conf = 0.95, type="all")

# Comparing:
# Ordinary Linear Regression
mean_litters.lm
## [1] 0.4152947
boot_ci_lm

Exercise 10

The data frame table.b3 in the MPV package contains data on gas mileage and 11 other variables for a sample of 32 automobiles.

(a) Construct a scatterplot of y (mpg) versus x1 (displacement). Is the relationship between these variables non-linear?

library(MPV)
## 
## Attaching package: 'MPV'
## The following object is masked from 'package:boot':
## 
##     motor
## The following object is masked from 'package:MASS':
## 
##     cement
library(lattice)

attach(table.b3) # in this way we directly have access to the variables

We constructed a scatter plot of y (mpg) against x1 (displacement).

plot(y ~ x1, xlab="displacement", ylab="mpg", main="mpg against displacement")

As we can see, the relationship between the two variables seems to be vaguely negatively linear. Nevertheless, a quadratic relationship could be more appropriate, as shown by the curvature of the ideal best fitting line as we approach the y axis, an evidence of non-linearity.

(b) Use the xyplot() function, and x11 (type of transmission) as a group variable. Is a linear model reasonable for these data?

We will now use the xyplot() function of the ‘lattice’ package. This function produces bivariate scatterplots or time-series plots. We call it on a formula describing the response variable and x1, and define x11 (type of transmission, binary categoric with 1=automatic and 0=manual) as conditioning variable.

xyplot(y ~ x1, group=x11, main="type of trasmission as group variable")

As we can see, arguing that the relationship is linear could be very inappropriate. In fact, it looks like there are two separate clusters in the data, one towards the left and one towards the right of the x axis, and each of them might be linear on its own.

(c) Fit the model relating y to x1 and x11 which gives two lines having possibly different slopes and intercepts. Check the diagnostics. Are there any influential observations? Are there any influential outliers?

We fit a model relating y to x1 and x11, using the ’*’ syntax which stands for x1, x11 and their interaction:

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
model1 <- lm(y ~ x1*x11, data=table.b3)
summary(model1) # print useful information relative to the fitted model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x1 * x11, data = table.b3)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -6.2712 -1.2660  0.1342  1.5181  4.6599 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  42.91963    2.73493  15.693 2.10e-15 ***
## x1           -0.11677    0.01984  -5.886 2.49e-06 ***
## x11         -13.46371    3.84413  -3.502 0.001567 ** 
## x1:x11        0.08165    0.02127   3.839 0.000647 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 2.566 on 28 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.851,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.8351 
## F-statistic: 53.33 on 3 and 28 DF,  p-value: 1.064e-11
# this allows us to have two lines with possibly different intercepts and slopes
plot(y ~ x1, data=table.b3)
coef <- model1$coefficients
abline(model1, col="red")
## Warning in abline(model1, col = "red"): only using the first two of 4
## regression coefficients
abline(a=coef[1]+coef[3],b=coef[2]+coef[4], col="green")

From the model’s summary we extract the information that the variables are significant, even if x1 is by far the most, by an order of \(10^5\). Let’s plot the diagnostics for the first model:

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(model1)

As we can see from the top-right plot, the hypothesis of Normality for the residuals seems to be sort of justified, except for a few possible outliers which have been labeled as 22, 5 and 15. On the other side, the bottom-right plot does not necessarily show evidence that 22 and 15 are in fact influential, since their Cook’s distance (which measures how much the removal of a given observation would affect the regression results) does not go beyond the threshold of 0.5, while a critical threshold of 1 has been proposed by the authors of the DAAG book.

On the other side, 5 lays beyond both those boundaries, so it is very likely to be an outlier. Notice that Cook’s distances take into account both the size and the leverage of the residuals as ingredients to measure their influence. On the other side, the two left plots do not realy suggest evidence of heteroscedasticity, since the behavior of the residuals against the fitted values is very close to constant.

(d) Plot the residuals against the variable x7 (number of transmission speeds), again using x11 as a group variable. Is there anything striking about this plot?

Let’s plot the residuals from the second model against the x7 variable (the number of transmission speeds, categorical with three levels).

library(ggplot2)
## Registered S3 methods overwritten by 'ggplot2':
##   method         from 
##   [.quosures     rlang
##   c.quosures     rlang
##   print.quosures rlang
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
ggplot(table.b3, aes(x = x7, y = model1$residuals, colour = x11)) +
  geom_point()

What strikes us is that the best fitting observations, that is those having the smallest residuals, seem to concentrate on the level 3 for x7, while the other two levels (4 and 5) contain observations with relatively large residuals. Intuitively, the type of transmission is a relevant predictor of miles/gallon if we are talking about a car having 3 transmission speeds, while the relationship deteriorates for other classes.

Exercise 1

The following table shows numbers of occasions when inhibition (i.e., no flow of current across a membrane) occurred within 120 s, for different concentrations of the protein peptide-C (data are used with the permission of Claudia Haarmann, who obtained these data in the course of her PhD research). The outcome yes implies that inhibition has occurred. conc 0.1 0.5 1 10 20 30 50 70 80 100 150 no 7 1 10 9 2 9 13 1 1 4 3 yes 0 0 3 4 0 6 7 0 0 1 7

Use logistic regression to model the probability of inhibition as a function of protein concentration.

The Logistic Regression is the process of estimating the parameters of a logistic model via maximum likelihood method. The analysis assumes that individuals respond independently with a probability, estimated from the data, that on a logistic scale is a linear function of the predictor variable. In R we use the function ‘glm()’, of ‘generalized linear models’, to perform the analysis.

# Variables:
protein_concentration <- c(.1, .5, 1, 10, 20, 30, 50, 70, 80, 100, 150)
no <- c(7, 1, 10, 9, 2, 9, 13, 1, 1, 4, 3)
yes <- c(0, 0, 3, 4, 0, 6, 7, 0, 0, 1 ,7)

# Total number: 
total <- no + yes

# Probability of inhibition:
probability_of_inhibition <- yes/total

# Logistic Regression:
inhib.glm <- glm(probability_of_inhibition ~ protein_concentration,
                 family=binomial(link="logit"), weights=total)

summary(inhib.glm)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = probability_of_inhibition ~ protein_concentration,

From the output of the ‘summary()’ function one can notice that both the intercept and the protein concentration are statistically significant.

The logistic regression coefficients give the change in the log odds of the outcome for a one unit increase in the predictor variable. In that case, we have that for every one unit change in protein concentration, the log odds of probability of inhibition (versus non-inhibition/flow of current across a membrane) increases by 0.012.

Below follows a graph showing the probability of inhibition versus protein concentration and the corresponding fitted logistic model.

#Plot:
plot(protein_concentration, probability_of_inhibition, pch=12,
    ylim=c(-0.1,1.1),xlim=c(-20.0,400.0),
    ylab="Probability of inhibition", xlab="Concentration of the protein peptide-C",
    cex.lab=.7, main="Probability of inhibition versus Protein concentration")

abline(h = 0)

Exercise 5

Use the function logisticsim() (in the DAAG package) to simulate data from a logistic regression model to study the glm() function. For example, you might try experiments such as the following:

(a) Simulate 100 observations from the model \[logit(x) = 2 − 4x\] for x = 0, 0.01, 0.02, . . . , 1.0. [This is the default setting for logisticsim().]

Let’s play around with the logisticsim() function, which simulates data from a logistic model. The first experiment uses the default values for the intercept, slope, and x data.

library(DAAG)

data <- logisticsim()

(b) Plot the responses (y) against the “dose” (x). Note how the pattern of 0s and 1s changes as x increases.

Let’s plot the results:

plot(data, main="simulated values from logistic model", xlab="dose", ylab="response")

Generally speaking, it looks like y gives a 1 response as x->0, while we witness more 0 responses as x->1, clearly as a result of the choice for the default parameters.

(c) Fit the logistic regression model to the simulated data, using the binomial family. Compare the estimated coefficients with the true coefficients. Are the estimated coefficients within about 2 standard errors of the truth?

We now fit a GLM using a binomial distribution (whose variant with logit link function (which is also the canonical one) is in fact what we call “logistic regression”).

model3 <- glm(data$y ~ data$x, family=binomial) 
# again, there is no need to explicit the link function

# since we are using the canonical, which is the default in this R routine
summary(model3)

## glm(formula = data$y ~ data$x, family = binomial)

Recall the true coefficients were 2 for the intercept and -4 for the slope of ‘x’. To comment on the difference between estimated and true parameters, we can try to see if the fitted ones are within 2 standard deviations from the truth, for example.

coef <- model3$coefficients
stds <- summary(model3)$coefficients[,2] # the parameters' standard deviations
(2 - 2 * stds[1]) <= coef[1] && coef[1] <= (2 + 2 * stds[1])
## [1] TRUE
(-4 - 2 * stds[2]) <= coef[2] && coef[2] <= (-4 + 2 * stds[2])
## [1] TRUE

(d) Compare the estimated logit function with the true logit function. How well do you think the fitted logistic model would predict future observations? For a concrete indication of the difference, simulate a new set of 100 observations at the same x values, using a specified pseudorandom number generator seed and the true model. Then simulate some predicted observations using the estimated model and the same seed.

Let’s try to understand how well would the fitted model predict future observations. Here we plot the true and fitted curves, exploiting the analytical form for the logistic model.

coef <- model3$coefficients
curve(exp(coef[1]+coef[2]*data$x)/(1+exp(coef[1]+coef[2]*data$x)), col=2, main="fitted and true logistic models", xlab="x", ylab="y")
curve(exp(2 - 4*data$x)/(1+exp(2 - 4*data$x)), add=T,col=3)

To answer the question, we will simulate 100 values as above using a predefined seed and the true model, and then compare with the predicted result under the fitted model.

seed <- 123 # the seed to be used
data2 <- logisticsim(seed=seed) # generate data
# predict values using the logistic formula
pred <- exp(coef[1]+coef[2]*data2$x)/(1+exp(coef[1]+coef[2]*data2$x)) 

pred <- ifelse(pred >= 0.5, 1, 0) 
# to give an output consistent with the domain of y, we decide to 
# put a threshold at 0.5 and classify as 1 the 
# predicted values which are above, and 0 those below

We can also compute some descriptive statistics of the two vectors to have an idea of their similarity:

mean(data2$y)
## [1] 0.4950495
mean(pred)
## [1] 0.4950495
var(data2$y)
## [1] 0.2524752
var(pred)
## [1] 0.2524752

As we can see, the mean of the two sets of values is very close, and the same holds for the dispersion, suggesting the predictions using the fitted model are very accurate.

Exercise 6

As in the previous exercise, the function poissonsim() allows for experimentation with Poisson regression. In particular, poissonsim() can be used to simulate Poisson responses with log-rates equal to a + bx, where a and b are fixed values by default.

(a) Simulate 100 Poisson responses using the model \[log(\lambda) = 2 − 4x\] for x = 0, 0.01, 0.02 . . . , 1.0. Fit a Poisson regression model to these data, and compare the estimated coefficients with the true coefficients. How well does the estimated model predict future observations?

Let’s simulate 100 values from a Poisson model with default parameters:

data3 <- poissonsim() # generate data
model4 <- glm(data3$y ~ data3$x, family=poisson) # fit the model
model4$coefficients
## (Intercept)     data3$x 
##    2.118262   -4.398362

To understand how well the estimated model predicts future observations we can repeat the process used with logistic regression.

coef <- model4$coefficients
plot(data3)
curve(exp(coef[1]+coef[2]*data3$x), add=T, col=2, main="fitted and true Poisson model")
curve(exp(2 - 4*data3$x), add=T,col=3)

To answer the question more precisely, we will simulate 100 values as above using a predefined seed and the true model, and then compare with the predicted result under the fitted model.

seed <- 123
data4 <- poissonsim(seed=seed) # generate data
pred <- exp(coef[1]+coef[2]*data4$x) # predict values using the estimated model
mean(data4$y)
## [1] 1.950495
mean(pred)
## [1] 1.891089
var(data4$y)
## [1] 6.807525
var(pred)
## [1] 4.600607

As we can see, the results are not really close, so we expect the fitted model will not have a really good generalization ability.

(b) Simulate 100 Poisson responses using the model \[log(\lambda) = 2 − bx\] where b is normally distributed with mean 4 and standard deviation 5. [Use the argument slope.sd=5 in the poissonsim() function.] How do the results using the poisson and quasipoisson families differ?

We now simulate 100 values using a Poisson model where the log of the lambda parameter depends linearly on a Normal random variable with mean 4 and std 5. To achieve this, we just need to specify slope.std=5, and b will be set to b + rnornm(n, slope.std) where n is the length of the x vector, as justified by the implementation of ‘poissonsim’ on Github at https://github.com/cran/DAAG/blob/master/R/poissonsim.R.

data5 <- poissonsim(b=4, slope.sd=5)
model5 <- glm(data5$y ~ data5$x, family=poisson)
summary(model5)

model6 <- glm(data5$y ~ data5$x, family=quasipoisson)
summary(model6)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = data5$y ~ data5$x, family = quasipoisson)

## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -229.65   -82.42   -40.00   -20.97   728.12

##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)    5.000      1.447   3.456 0.000808 ***
## data5$x        5.180      1.729   2.995 0.003468 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for quasipoisson family taken to be 49352.8)
## 
##     Null deviance: 2625552  on 100  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 1910521  on  99  degrees of freedom
## AIC: NA
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 8

Recall that quasipoisson uses quasi-likelihood as an estimation procedure under the hood. As we can see, the estimates for the parameters are left unchanged, since the estimating equations are still the same. On the other side, the standard deviations of the estimates have increased. In fact, with quasipoisson regression we are relaxing the assumption that the dispersion parameter \(\phi\) of the Poisson model is equal to 1. Then, it might be the case that the model was suffering from overdispersion, that is a \(\phi\) > 1, by which the variance of \(Y\) is greater than its theoretical value.
